Sup senpai. Some general feedback from one writefag to another:

If you do greentext, you should do it in a stream of consciousness style. Try more line breaks. Observe:

>Suddenly, the streetlights turned on
>And then he saw her
>Her furry body her pointy ears, her long tail...
>There she was
>And he loved the sight
>It far surpassed anything they had described to him, but it didn’t matter now. He was there, and he could finally do what he had dreamed countless nights
>Losing his virginity in the best way possible

Notice how much the formatting changes the flow of the piece? Greentext is so unique because it allows for prose with the style of poetry. If you want to write plain prose, that's fine too. In which case, you don't need the ">" attached to it. Use the ">" only if you're doing a green.
Mechanically, it's sound, though in practice I always try to show and not tell. For example, when you say "he loved the sight," you should describe what that feels or looks like to your main character

>His fingers went numb and jaw slack when the light really hit her slender form, curled up against the alley's walls
>He could feel his heart beat faster, and all the knots of tension and anxiety in the ropes of his stomach went away with one look at her stacked frame

Again, that's probably too much, but you get the point. Show, don't tell.

My best advice to you is to read some things from the pastebin to get a hang of the writing style. I know self shilling is tacky, but I wrote a story called Beating the Heat that I think does a few things well. Might be worth checking out some other authors as well? Strong is solid.

https://pastebin.com/Ysev4tB5

I'm going to head to bed here but I'll try and stay up if you have any questions my guy. and welcome to the writefag guild

Just some notes as I read it, and please understand I'm trying to be helpful;
First, you're writing more in prose, rather than greentext. Greentext doesn't really handle more than a sentence per line. If you prefer prose, then stick with it as I've always struggled with the green format myself.
>But after a while, he got up from his bed
Some scene establishment would be helpful. We go from exposition to suddenly what looks like the middle of a scene.
As an example:
>... not in what you would call a safe zone past 6PM. Anon (or even just He if you don't want names) thought about this she-wolf and this alleyway as he wondered if these rumours were even true, but after a while, he got up... etc.

The sentence structure's fairly haphazard, but I think you'll benefit by just reading some of the stories in this thread to get an idea how to rectify many of these issues. This also applies to trimming down sentences to be punchier for small details:
>The bus stop wasn't far (from) his home, so he went there, stepped in and found himself a seat.
Consider;
>He went to the nearby bus stop and, as soon as one arrived, found himself a seat.
Or if you really want to pare down the sentence.
>He took a bus...
You can save bigger details for more important aspects. It gives punch to things that need the details, as readers can fill the blanks themselves.

>He (was) almost asleep when the driver said.
The driver's talking, so use quotation marks there, and later when our protagonist is thinking to himself, you could try 'like this' or even nothing at all, instead putting:
>he thought about how fitting this seemed for a horror story.

In terms of the she-wolf, that's important enough you could spend some extra details in the description. We have that she's furry, has pointy ears and a long tail. If the lights are on, we could use the colour, her build, her height, if we can see her eyes, etc.
